In CSS, **`display: flex`** and **`display: grid`** are **layout systems** used to arrange elements on a page. Both solve layout problems, but they are designed for **different purposes**.

***

# 1️⃣ `display: flex` (Flexbox)

### ✅ What it is

**Flexbox** is a **one‑dimensional layout system**.\
It works **either in a row OR in a column**, not both at the same time.

👉 Best for **aligning items in a single direction**.

***

### ✅ How it works

When you apply `display: flex` to a container:

```css
.container {
  display: flex;
}
```

*   The container becomes a **flex container**
*   Its children become **flex items**

***

### ✅ Default Behavior

```css
flex-direction: row;
```

Items are placed **horizontally from left to right**.

***

### ✅ Example



```css
.container {
  display: flex;
  gap: 10px;
}
```

✅ Output:

    Item 1 | Item 2 | Item 3

***

### ✅ Common Flexbox Properties

#### On Container

```css
display: flex;
flex-direction: row | column;
justify-content: flex-start | center | space-between;
align-items: flex-start | center | stretch;
flex-wrap: wrap;
```

#### On Items

```css
flex: 1;
align-self: center;
```

***

### ✅ Best Use Cases for Flexbox

✔ Navigation bars\
✔ Buttons aligned in a row\
✔ Centering content\
✔ Small UI components (cards, headers, footers)

***

# 2️⃣ `display: grid` (CSS Grid)

### ✅ What it is

**CSS Grid** is a **two‑dimensional layout system**.\
It controls **rows AND columns together**.

👉 Best for **overall page layouts and complex designs**.

***

### ✅ How it works

```css
.container {
  display: grid;
}
```

*   You define **rows and columns**
*   Items are placed into a **grid structure**

***

### ✅ Example

```css
.container {
  display: grid;
  grid-template-columns: 1fr 1fr 1fr;
  gap: 10px;
}
```

✅ Creates **3 equal columns**

***

### ✅ HTML Example



```css
.container {
  display: grid;
  grid-template-columns: 1fr 3fr;
}
```

✅ Sidebar + Main layout

***

### ✅ Common Grid Properties

```css
grid-template-rows
grid-template-columns
gap
grid-column
grid-row
grid-template-areas
```

***

### ✅ Grid Areas Example

```css
.container {
  display: grid;
  grid-template-areas:
    "header header"
    "sidebar main";
}

.header { grid-area: header; }
.sidebar { grid-area: sidebar; }
.main { grid-area: main; }
```

✅ Very readable layout control

***

# 3️⃣ Flexbox vs Grid (Key Differences)

| Feature        | Flexbox            | Grid                  |
| -------------- | ------------------ | --------------------- |
| Dimension      | 1D (row OR column) | 2D (rows AND columns) |
| Layout control | Content-based      | Layout-based          |
| Best for       | Small UI parts     | Page layouts          |
| Alignment      | Excellent          | Excellent             |
| Learning curve | Easier             | Slightly harder       |

***

# 4️⃣ When to Use What?

### ✅ Use **Flexbox** when:

*   Layout is **one-dimensional**
*   Items should adjust based on content
*   You need alignment (center, space-between)

✅ Example:

```css
header {
  display: flex;
  justify-content: space-between;
}
```

***

### ✅ Use **Grid** when:

*   You need **rows + columns**
*   You want **structured page layouts**
*   Design is fixed or semi‑fixed

✅ Example:

```css
page {
  display: grid;
  grid-template-columns: 250px 1fr;
}
```

***

# 5️⃣ Using Flexbox AND Grid Together (Very Common)

✅ Grid for **page layout**
✅ Flexbox for **components inside grid**

    Page (Grid)
     ├── Header (Flex)
     ├── Sidebar (Flex)
     └── Main Content (Flex)

***

# 6️⃣ Interview‑Ready Answer

> **Flexbox is a one‑dimensional layout system used for arranging items in a row or column, while CSS Grid is a two‑dimensional system used for creating complex layouts with rows and columns. Flexbox is ideal for components, and Grid is best for page-level layouts.**

